<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Medium sized (7.5-11.6 mm), dark brown species with characteristic large silver microtrichose fasciae on terga 2-4 in males (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23C</figureCitation>
), and silver michrotrichose ornamentation on scutum in both sexes (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23A, B</figureCitation>
); basoflagellomere with rounded apex, 1.6-1.8 times longer than wide in male (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., antenna, lateral view. A outer side, male B inner side, male outer side, female. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377394" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">33A, B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Male.</emphasis>
Head. Antennae black to dark brown; basoflagellomere rounded, 1.6-1.8 times as long as wide, and ca. 2.3 times as long as pedicel; large fossette dorsomedial and dorsolateral; arista brown and thickened at basal one third, covered with dense microtrichia, ca. 1.8 times as long as basoflagellomere (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., antenna, lateral view. A outer side, male B inner side, male outer side, female. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377394" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">33A, B</figureCitation>
); face and frons black with gray microtrichia, face covered with dense whitish gray, and frons with yellowish gray pile; oral margin shiny with microtrichose lateral areas; lunule shiny black, bare; vertex covered with gray microtrichia; vertex isosceles, with long, pale whitish yellow pile mixed with black pile on the ocellar triangle; ocellar triangle equilateral; eyes covered with dense pile; occiput with gray-yellow pile, covered with a dense, gray microtrichia; eye contiguity 8-12 facets long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Thorax. Scutum and scutellum black with bronze luster, covered with dense, erect, yellow pile; scutum with conspicuous silver microtrichose ornamentation (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23A</figureCitation>
); posterodorsal part of anterior anepisternum, posterior anepisternum (except anteroventral angle), anterior anepimeron, dorsomedial anepimeron, and posterodorsal and anteroventral parts of katepisternum with long, pale yellow pile and grayish microtrichia; wings entirely covered with microtrichia; wing veins brown; calypteres and halteres pale yellow; legs mostly black, except yellowish tip of femora, basal and apical part of tibiae and brown tarsi ventrally; pile on legs pale yellow; metafemur moderately incrassate, ca. four times longer than wide; pile on metafemur long, and ca. half to two thirds of width of metafemur.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Abdomen. Tapering, 1.2 times longer than mesonotum; terga dark, with broad silver microtrichose fasciae; tergum 2 with pale orange lateral maculae; pile on terga all yellow (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23C</figureCitation>
); sterna dark brown, covered with long whitish yellow pile.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
Male genitalia. Apical part of anterior surstyle lobe rhomboid shape, approximately as long as wide, covered with dense, short pile (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="F34" captionText="Figure 34. Male genitalia. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, lateral view B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, ventral view C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., hypandrium, lateral view. Abbreviations: al-anterior surstyle lobe, bp-basolateral protrusion, l-lingula. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure34" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377395" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">34A</figureCitation>
: al); posterior surstyle lobe oval with basolateral protrusion (lateral hump) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="F34" captionText="Figure 34. Male genitalia. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, lateral view B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, ventral view C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., hypandrium, lateral view. Abbreviations: al-anterior surstyle lobe, bp-basolateral protrusion, l-lingula. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure34" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377395" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">34A, B</figureCitation>
: bp); hypandrium sickle-shaped, without lateral projections; lingula (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="F34" captionText="Figure 34. Male genitalia. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, lateral view B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., epandrium, ventral view C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., hypandrium, lateral view. Abbreviations: al-anterior surstyle lobe, bp-basolateral protrusion, l-lingula. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure34" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377395" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">34C</figureCitation>
: l).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Female.</emphasis>
Similar to the male except for normal sexual dimorphism and for the following characteristics: basoflagellomere ca. 1.8 times longer than wide, fossette dorsolateral (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 33" captionStartId="F33" captionText="Figure 33. Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., antenna, lateral view. A outer side, male B inner side, male outer side, female. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377394" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">33C</figureCitation>
); frons with microtrichose vittae along eye margins; frons covered with mostly gray-yellow pile mixed with black ones; ocellar triangle covered with black pile; ventral margin of metafemur with sparse pilosity, only individual pile longer; lateral side of terga, anterior two third of tergum 2 and all tergum 5 with whitish pile; terga 2-4 with short adpressed black pile medially; microtrichose fasciae on terga 3 and 4 narrower (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="F23" captionText="Figure 23. Body parts, dorsal view. A Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, male B Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., thorax, female C Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, male D Merodon trianguloculus sp. nov., abdomen, female E Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, male F Merodon kawamurae, abdomen, female. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure23" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377384" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">23D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vujic, Likov &amp; Radenkovic" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Merodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="trianguloculus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trianguloculus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">trianguloculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
derives from the Latin adjective 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">triangulus</emphasis>
(triangular) and Latin noun 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">loculus</emphasis>
(spot) and describes the distinctive triangular silver pollinose fasciae on the abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vujic, Likov &amp; Radenkovic" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Merodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Merodon trianguloculus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trianguloculus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Merodon trianguloculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. was recorded only in Turkmenistan (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution map of Merodon serrulatus species group." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.909.46838.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/377368" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Preferred environment: open areas extending to the forest zone; unimproved grassland; adults resting on the stones and in flight between grasses at the top of Dushak Mountain. Flowers visited: no data. Flight period: May-June.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
